<p><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">On contemporary systems, the use of the sticky bit has been extended. The Single UNIX Specification allows the sticky bit to be set for a directory. If the bit is set for a directory, a file in the directory can be removed or renamed only if the user has write permission for the directory and meets one of the following criteria:</span></p>
<ul style=" list-style-type: disc;">
<li style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">
<p><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">Owns the file</span></p>
</li>
<li style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">
<p><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">Owns the directory</span></p>
</li>
<li style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">
<p><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">Is the superuser</span></p>
<p><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">The directories </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Courier;">/tmp </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">and </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Courier;">/var/tmp </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">are typical candidates for the sticky bit — they are directories in which any user can typically create files. The permissions for these two directories are often read, write, and execute for everyone (user, group, and other). But users should not be able to delete or rename files owned by others.</span></p>
</li>
</ul>
